From: bluecat <lmhtq1991@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 29 May 2026 11:25:00 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] Phase C-6 L26-L31: interpreter prologue fully cap-aware — prologue TRAVERSED

After cap-BLR (0100) bridged codecache→libjvm.so, the trampoline
executes runtime helpers and returns. A cascade of interpreter
cap-load/store gaps then surfaced — all the same root cause (HotSpot
stock integer ldr/str/stp/sub on cap-valued pointers strips tags or
mis-strides cap-sized frame slots). Fixed layer by layer via gdb:

  L26: trampoline arg-shift miscount. call_VM_base puts the JavaThread
       in c_rarg0 PLUS N args in c_rarg1.., so the occupied-arg count
       is N+1 there but N in the leaf path. Now shift a FIXED 5 regs
       (c0..c4 → c1..c5) unconditionally; real args always occupy a
       c0.. prefix, extra shifted garbage is ignored by the callee.

  L27/L28: rmethod (r12, caller-saved) is clobbered across call_VM.
       interp call_VM_base now reloads rmethod via cap-LDR after the
       call, mirroring restore_bcp/restore_locals.

  L27 cont.: interp getters (get_method/get_const/get_constant_pool/
       get_constant_pool_cache/get_cpool_and_tags/restore_bcp/
       restore_locals/restore_constant_pool_cache/save_bcp) all used
       integer ldr/str on cap pointers → cap-LDR/cap-STR.

  L29: generate_fixed_frame stored Method*/mdp/mirror/rlocals/rcpool/
       rfp/lr/sender-sp via integer stp — strips tags AND uses 8-byte
       stride that misplaces the 2nd reg vs the cap-sized (16B) frame
       slots that the cap-LDR getters read. New cap_stp_sp/cap_stp_sp_pre
       helpers (sp encodes as #31, not sp->encoding()).

  L30: get_method_counters loaded MethodCounters* (a cap) via integer
       ldr → cap-LDR.

  L31: bang_stack_shadow_pages + bang_stack_with_offset did integer
       sub(rscratch2, sp, off) stripping sp's cap tag → str faulted.
       cap-SUB (imm12 and LSL#12 forms) preserves the stack capability.

RESULT: the interpreter method-entry prologue is FULLY TRAVERSED with
no PROT_CHERI_TAG fault. The JVM no longer crashes in normal_entry; it
now reaches a wait/parked state (3 threads: launcher joining, a JVM
service thread in cond_wait, the Java main thread in signal handling).
The remaining issue is a hang (likely the SIGPROT handler looping on a
new unforwarded fault deeper in execution), NOT a prologue crash. This
is a categorical milestone: from "crashes ~5 insns into the interpreter"
to "executes the entire prologue + runtime callbacks and runs on".

Layers resolved this session: L25 (cap-BLR/trampoline) through L31.
Session: 35 commits, 87 build iterations.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

